                        <div id="iul" class="script"><span class="say">Hey </span><span class="fill">&lt;NAME&gt;</span><span class="say">, I don’t mean to bore you guys, but has anyone explained the difference between a term and whole life to you?

Okay, well term is short for terminate. You know, 10, 20, 30 years — whatever it may be — it expires. And whole life is called whole life because, well, it lasts your whole life.

Are you guys aware of what percentage of term policies actually pay out of people passing away within that term they take out?</span>
<span class="silent">LET THEM GUESS</span>

<span class="say">Okay </span><span class="fill">&lt;NAME&gt;</span><span class="say">, that’s a good guess, but according to the national insurance association — and feel free to look this up — less than 2% of term policies actually pay out.

So the insurance company knows that, and they’ve done actuarial studies on this, that there’s a 98% chance you’re going to outlive that term. And that’s why term is so cheap, because the insurance company knows that more than likely you’re going to outlive it, and then when you do outlive it and go to reapply for insurance, well it’s 10, 20, 30 times more expensive because you’re 10, 20, 30 years older — and that’s even if you’re eligible at the time.

Versus on whole life, there’s really no situation where you come out behind in a whole life policy, because that policy is paying out. You never have to worry about it expiring or outliving it, because it’s going to last until you are 120 years old.

And </span><span class="fill">&lt;NAME&gt;</span><span class="say">, I still sit down with some clients that tell me, “Hey, whole life sounds great but I really only care about having protection in place while I’m raising the family, covering the bills, and making sure everyone is okay, and then after that I’m really not concerned with it.”

And I still tell them to take out a whole life policy because 20–30 years down the road, with this IUL with Mutual of Omaha, if you decide you no longer want it, you can simply go and surrender it and you will get all the money you paid into it back refunded to you, plus interest.

So either A, that policy is paying out because it never expires, or B, 20–30 years from now if you decide down the road you don’t want it, no worries — you simply get all the cash value you’ve paid into it plus interest. Does that make sense?</span>

<span class="note">If they already have a term:</span>
<span class="say">The only downside here is they are a lot more strict on these whole life policies than they are term, so we don’t want to go canceling anything until we know we can get you approved for this. And if you do, then I will help you get that one switched over.</span>

<span class="note">Write this down:</span>
<span class="silent">80% LIVING BENEFITS</span>
<span class="silent">BUILDS CASH VALUE</span>

<span class="say">So God willing, if you’re alive and well down the road, you’ll have two options: you can either continue the coverage as supplemental life coverage, or you can surrender the policy for the cash value.</span>

<span class="say">Perfect, now write down </span><span class="fill">&lt;HIGHEST OPTION&gt;</span><span class="say">, then </span><span class="fill">&lt;NEXT OPTION&gt;</span><span class="say"> below that, then </span><span class="fill">&lt;LOWEST OPTION&gt;</span><span class="say"> below that.</span>

